// ============================================================================
// NS Smoothness: Axiomatic Half-Derivative — Results Summary
//
// Instead of numerically computing H^{3/2}, we axiomatize D^{1/2}
// and let Z3 reason about whether NS structural constraints permit
// or forbid blow-up.
//
// Half-derivative axioms:
//   Interpolation: H32² ≤ Ω · P           (D^{1/2} ∘ D^{1/2} = D¹)
//   Sobolev:       ||∇v||_∞ ≤ C · H32     (embedding in 3D)
//   Norm ordering: Ω ≤ H32 ≤ P            (k² ≤ k³ ≤ k⁴)
//
// NS structural equations:
//   dE/dt = -2νΩ        (energy dissipation)
//   dΩ/dt = S - 2νP     (enstrophy evolution)
//   0 ≤ S ≤ ||∇v||_∞·Ω (stretching bound)
//   P ≥ Ω               (Poincaré)
//   E ≤ 1               (bounded energy)
//
// RESULTS (Z3, each in isolated context):
//
//   T1: Base axioms consistent                     → SAT ✓
//   T2: H32 > 100 with bounded energy              → SAT ✓ (gap is REAL)
//   T3: H32 > 100 AND enstrophy growing             → SAT ✓ (blow-up PERMITTED)
//   T4: 2D: S=0 AND enstrophy growing               → UNSAT ✓ (2D is smooth)
//   T5: Saturated stretching + growth                → SAT ✓ (worst case is consistent)
//
// INTERPRETATION:
//
//   The half-derivative axioms DO NOT prevent blow-up.
//   Z3 finds models where all axioms hold, H32 is arbitrarily large,
//   and enstrophy is growing — the blow-up scenario is structurally
//   consistent.
//
//   The 2D control (S=0) correctly gives UNSAT: without stretching,
//   dΩ/dt = -2νP < 0, so enstrophy must decrease. This confirms the
//   axioms are correctly capturing the physics.
//
//   The 3D case allows blow-up because:
//     S ≤ H32 · Ω ≤ P · Ω  (stretching can be as large as P · Ω)
//     2νP grows linearly in P
//     P · Ω grows faster (quadratically if Ω ~ P)
//   So for large enough Ω, stretching overwhelms dissipation.
//
//   This is the ½-derivative gap, now AXIOMATICALLY VERIFIED:
//   the structural axioms of D^{1/2} combined with NS equations
//   are INSUFFICIENT to prove smoothness.
//
// COMPARISON WITH SPECTRAL COMB:
//
//   Spectral Comb: assert(Re ≠ 1/2) → UNSAT. Antisymmetry FORCES Re = 1/2.
//   NS:            assert(H32 > 100 ∧ dΩ/dt > 0) → SAT. Axioms PERMIT blow-up.
//
//   The antisymmetry axiom is STRONG ENOUGH to close the gap.
//   The half-derivative axioms are NOT STRONG ENOUGH.
//   The missing ingredient: a structural property of NS solutions that
//   is not captured by interpolation + Sobolev + energy dissipation.
//
// FILES:
//   ns_hd_consistent.kleis  — T1: base axiom consistency
//   ns_hd_large.kleis       — T2: H32 > 100 (gap test)
//   ns_hd_blowup.kleis      — T3: blow-up scenario
//   ns_hd_2d.kleis           — T4: 2D control (expects UNSAT)
//   ns_hd_saturated.kleis   — T5: saturated stretching
//
// ============================================================================
